article.description:
Michael Finley scored 28 points and Steve Nash
added 22 as the Dallas Mavericks beat the Golden State Warriors 107-105 Saturday night.
article.headline: Mavs pick up NBA-best 44th victory
article.linkText: Mavs survive close call against lowly Warriors
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The Dallas Mavericks' 44th victory of the season was a struggle.
Finley

Michael Finley scored 28 points and Steve Nash added 22 as the Mavericks beat the Golden State Warriors 107-105 on Saturday night. Dirk Nowitzki added 19 points and 11 rebounds, and Raef LaFrentz had 15 points and nine rebounds for the Mavericks, who won for the seventh time in eight games and assumed the league lead in victories, one win ahead of the Sacramento Kings. "We were lucky to win," said Nash. "We didn't play very well and we just survived." Rookie Jason Richardson scored 21 points and Bob Sura added 14 for the Warriors, who have lost 11 of 13. Antawn Jamison and Gilbert Arenas each scored 13 points for Golden State. "This is not one of those negative losses where you go out and get killed," Richardson said. "I think it was very positive for us to come out here against one of the teams competing for a world championship. I'm pleased we played hard, but we want to win." The victory was Dallas' 12th straight over Golden State. Earlier in the season, the Mavericks rallied from a 21-point deficit and beat the Warriors 116-106. "They have a good team with a lot of talent," Nowitzki said. "They just have to learn to win games like that." The Mavericks' defensive struggles continued. They have allowed 100 points in four of their last five games. "Our effort defensively was not that good," LaFrentz said. "Giving up 102 points to them is unacceptable, but we got the win." Golden State trailed by as many as 12 in the first half. The Warriors opened the fourth quarter with a 14-4 run and took a 92-91 lead -- their first of the game -- when Chris Mills made a layup with 6:46 remaining. Nash hit consecutive 3-pointers and scored eight straight points for Dallas. LaFrentz made a layup with 2:34 remaining to give the Mavericks the lead for good, 102-100. Nowitzki's 15-foot jumper with 1:06 left extended the Mavericks' lead to 104-101. A layup by Arenas with 59 seconds left cut the deficit to one. Richardson had a basket disallowed on an offensive foul with 34.6 seconds left that would have given the Warriors a 105-104 lead. Richardson hit a 12-footer with 7.9 seconds remaining, pulling the Warriors within 106-105. Nash made one of two free throws with 7.0 seconds left, and Sura missed the rim with a 25-foot shot at the buzzer. The Mavericks led 85-78 heading into the final quarter. Dallas took a 57-54 halftime lead behind 20 first-half points by Finley. The Mavericks once again relied on the balanced attack of Finley, Nowitzki and Nash for points down the stretch in a tight game. "That's why our team is so good," Nash said. "Because we don't have to rely on one guy." Game notes
Golden State's 12-game losing streak to Dallas is the Warriors' longest in team history. ... Eduardo Najera started for the third time this season for the Mavericks. Najera had nine rebounds, five offensive, and Dallas held a 47-46 rebounding edge. Golden State started the night as the league's top rebounding team. ...Dallas is 35-6 when scoring 100 or more points. ...The Warriors are 6-24 on the road. ...Golden State missed 11 of 29 free throws.
